abstract = {A dielectrically adjusted version of the RISM equation for the situation$\backslash$nof ions in mixed solvents is applied to model mixtures of water with$\backslash$nmethanol in concentrations covering the complete concentration range.$\backslash$nCalculated structures from the integral equation theory are compared$\backslash$nto corresponding results from NVT molecular dynamics simulations.$\backslash$nThe structure calculated from the integral equation is generally$\backslash$nin good agreement with the molecular dynamics results. The agreement$\backslash$nin calculated energies between integral equation theory and molecular$\backslash$ndynamics simulations are also generally good over the entire concentration$\backslash$nrange for the specific model applied. For the first time this type$\backslash$nof integral equation theory is also applied to the direct calculation$\backslash$nof free energy. For the specific water model the free energy is lower$\backslash$nthan the experimental value for pure water. Under-predictions of$\backslash$nthe structure and corresponding higher entropy for the specific water$\backslash$nmodel might be one of the reasons for these results. The dielectric$\backslash$nconstant in a uniform liquid mixture can be described in terms of$\backslash$nthe dipole moments of the molecules involved and the molecular correlation$\backslash$nfunctions for the different molecular pair combinations in the mixture.$\backslash$nIn this work I reformulate the theory into a corresponding interaction$\backslash$nsite formulation. The reformulated theory is illustrated for the$\backslash$nwater/methanol model mixtures.},
